column104: Additional remarks

I tried to keep separate the paper and the artifact. I think the paper should include more details on the experiment etc. then, that information is imo not needed again in the artifact. I agreed with most of the proposed guidelines, but nevertheless, I think there should be a difference between a research artifact (just something to show your idea/experiment) and a full-blown open source project with all the bells and whistles and support until infinity. There should be a balance between making artifacts reusable, but without demanding for the moon.

column104: in my experience the reuse of an artifact can occur in many ways that would change the my answers, e.g., i might just want to reuse models or data as opposed to reusing the processing or algorithms done by the authors. I have answered according to my most common reuse experience, which often reuses the model/data parts but less so the code parts.

column9: Tooling that is easily (yet freely) available, stable, fast and ensures artifacts to be edited in the long-run.

It was a Ph.D. student who wanted to use my (meta) models. He/She had severe trouble in setting up the infrastructure (Eclipse Ecore). Additionally, it seemed to be a real issue in understanding how to work with models from the Java perspective ("that are just classes and objects, where is the model?").

Evolution consequences: Shared models some years ago might not be possible to be loaded with current tools (e.g., metamodel has evolved, current tools evolved and they are no longer compatible so you need to take an ancient version of the tool incompatible with new functionalities you want to use)
Lack of adoption of libraries: Libraries of models and model transformations have been developed in the last years, but I have doubts if they were successful or if they reached an acceptable level of adoption. The idea is not bad but I never used them.
Lack of real or realistic models: Big models exist but in most of the cases they are incomplete (e.g., https://wiki.eclipse.org/Capella/Samples/IFE)

With regard to the use of artifacts:
-Missing or outdated documentation about setup and use
-Incompatibility between different versions and tools. For example, some tools need Eclipse Neon to work, others need Eclipse Photon. Depending on the differences, one may need several Eclipse versions and sometimes different Java versions.
Incompatible modeling languages; models that don't parse correctly; repositories that cease being supported; languages that become obsolete

Deprecation of the underlying toolchain, the documentation of the tools in general and the lack of replication packages. The last is the biggest issue.
column24: The package must contain a clear explanation how to setup up the artifact and perform a typical use case of the associated evaluation tasks. It should state clear the prerequisites, e.g., Eclipse version X.Y, Ubuntu 20.04, ksh. And this documentation should be sufficient to setup everything from such how-to without additional knowledge and insights. In some cases Docker, Podman, Snap, Flatpack etc. can be used to reduce the number of dependencies, but then the documentation must contain at least a reference how to get those running on a standard platform.

The questions in this survey should be part of the final guideline for replication packages. Other domains already have such instructions. I found it very helpful to look at efforts made in the natural sciences. They are way ahead of the modeling and software eningeering community. Especially regarding practice. It is necessary to have guideline that separate in a "before you start with your research section" and a checklist for creating the replication packages. Subsequently, you need a wiki or forum for a collection of good practices. 

Also the guideline is also an artifact and needs proper documentation. ;-)

BTW: I find this work very important.

column104: I did not really reflect in full detail on all aspects of the proposed guidelines. The "seem" to be complete to me, and most of the things that I consider relevant seem to have been indicated. Perhaps one thing I would add: for some artefacts we have produced, we have used a "readthedocs.io" user manual, fully integrated with the GitHub repository on which the artefact itself is shared and versioned. Whenever a new version of the artefact is created and released, the user manual on "readthedocs.io" will get updated as well. There are other solutions, but such an automated online web-based user manual seems like a very desirable thing to have, and it integrates well into a continuous integration process. Having CI/CD for MDE artifact development seems very desirable in general (even if it requires effort for the artefact producers). Specifying the (open source or other) licence of the artefact is also crucial.

column24: Just a comment on the question "The artifact shall indicate" "XXX used to develop it"-- this is difficult for me to answer, as it depends: Let's say someone developed an artifact using UML, maybe generate code. column9: Being MDE artifacts part of research projects, their obsolescence can be rapid and uncontrolled due to the variety of application domains for MDE and scarcity of working forces. From a research-wise point of view is more convenient a publication rather than the maintenance of MDE artifacts from previous publications.

Software sharing: challenges in packaging software in a reusable form. Often, this can take significantly more time than producing the research and software in the first place. Support infrastructure for streamlining the required processes would be really helpful.

Sharing of models etc: the special encoding required for many models can make it very difficult to package large artefact collections in a way that is easily inspectable by others.
